WEBVTT

00:08.878 --> 00:08.921
PENNYWORTH#108
"Sandie Shaw"
Closed captioned

00:12.447 --> 00:14.927
I'm sorry about your
husband, Mrs. Thwaite.

00:14.971 --> 00:16.842
Let's put the past
behind us, Mrs. Gaunt.

00:16.886 --> 00:18.496
Let's show the world
what can be done

00:18.540 --> 00:20.846
when two women reason together.

00:23.153 --> 00:24.546
Do you like parties, Martha?

00:27.810 --> 00:29.333
MARTHA: You need to go get your sister away from that man.

00:29.377 --> 00:30.508
He's in league
with the devil.

00:30.552 --> 00:31.814
I mean, really he is.

00:31.857 --> 00:33.729
How did you two

00:33.772 --> 00:35.296
end up working together?

00:35.339 --> 00:36.645
We're not with
the No-Name League.

00:36.688 --> 00:37.820
CROWLEY:
Next you'll tell me

00:37.863 --> 00:40.170
you're not spying on them
for the CIA.

00:40.214 --> 00:43.043
What do you want, Crowley?I want your soul, of course.

00:48.048 --> 00:50.963
MARTHA: Thomas, will you please tell us what happened?

00:51.007 --> 00:53.444
We were never there.
You understand?

00:53.488 --> 00:55.838
My God. James.

00:55.881 --> 00:57.231
Hello, Frances.

00:57.274 --> 00:58.406
I thought you were dead.

00:58.449 --> 00:59.842
When the time is right,

00:59.885 --> 01:02.149
I shall reveal myself publicly.

01:02.192 --> 01:05.021
And then I will destroy
my enemies

01:05.065 --> 01:06.718
and lead this country back
to greatness.

01:06.762 --> 01:08.590
The Raven Society

01:08.633 --> 01:12.159
is on the cusp
of a new dawn.

01:12.202 --> 01:14.204
It'll shock the world.

01:14.248 --> 01:16.119
Are you with me?!

01:16.163 --> 01:18.121
Yes, yes, yes!

01:19.340 --> 01:20.471
Will you marry me?

01:20.515 --> 01:21.690
Yes.

01:21.733 --> 01:23.126
Yes, I will.

01:25.520 --> 01:27.522
Esme!

01:27.565 --> 01:29.698
ALFRED:
Captain Curzon,

01:29.741 --> 01:30.742
he has been waiting,

01:30.786 --> 01:31.830
waiting all this time

01:31.874 --> 01:32.831
to pay me back.

01:32.875 --> 01:34.833
Anything?

01:37.836 --> 01:39.273
MRS. PIKE:
I don't even know
his first name.

01:39.316 --> 01:40.665
Just clean his house,
that's all.

01:40.709 --> 01:42.189
Have you any idea
where he's gone?

01:45.627 --> 01:47.455
You're supposed to be dead.Well, I'm not.

02:30.715 --> 02:33.196
How's your mum?

02:33.240 --> 02:34.850
All right.

02:34.893 --> 02:36.721
I like your mum.

02:36.765 --> 02:39.071
Why aren't you dead?

02:39.115 --> 02:40.725
It's a good trick, eh?

02:40.769 --> 02:42.336
I'd tell you how,
but I'd have

02:42.379 --> 02:47.297
to implicate other parties,
so I'll say nowt.

02:47.341 --> 02:50.213
Tell me why I shouldn't give
the old bill a shout.

02:50.257 --> 02:51.954
Why would you?

02:51.997 --> 02:54.391
I've done nothing to you.

02:54.435 --> 02:56.828
Recently.

02:56.872 --> 02:58.613
Why are you here?

02:58.656 --> 03:00.354
How did you know about Curzon?

03:00.397 --> 03:03.313
I've got important friends, me.

03:03.357 --> 03:05.968
And you're the talk
of the town, you two.

03:06.011 --> 03:09.276
Why? Curzon's a nobody.

03:09.319 --> 03:11.713
Nobody's nobody.

03:11.756 --> 03:13.758
Why'd he kill Esme?

03:15.934 --> 03:18.154
To get at me.

03:18.198 --> 03:21.766
Revenge. He thinks
I disrespected him.

03:21.810 --> 03:25.248
Oh, I see.

03:25.292 --> 03:27.207
It were your fault, then.

03:27.250 --> 03:28.817
Thought as much.

03:28.860 --> 03:30.862
Why else would anyone hurt

03:30.906 --> 03:34.388
such a lovely, innocent
lass like her?

03:34.431 --> 03:37.565
What did you do
to disrespect him?

03:37.608 --> 03:40.002
What's any of this got to do
with you?

03:40.045 --> 03:42.613
I just want justice for Esme,
same as you.

03:44.354 --> 03:46.051
I loved her.

03:46.095 --> 03:49.098
You barely knew her.

03:49.141 --> 03:51.056
She was my fiancÃ©e.

03:51.100 --> 03:53.972
I dare say you were
very fond of her.

03:54.016 --> 03:56.018
A man's love's not the same,
though, is it?

03:56.061 --> 03:58.325
You've less
feeling in you.

03:58.368 --> 04:01.066
Any road,

04:01.110 --> 04:04.113
our lad's away,
pointing no fingers.

04:05.723 --> 04:08.335
We have to catch
the bugger again.

04:08.378 --> 04:09.858
Best team up, eh?

04:09.901 --> 04:13.644
I'm gonna go now.

04:13.688 --> 04:16.821
Have I done somewhat
to offend you somehow?

04:16.865 --> 04:20.085
No. You're mad, that's all.

04:20.129 --> 04:21.739
Don't be like that.

04:21.783 --> 04:23.306
We could help each other.

04:23.350 --> 04:25.787
Good-bye.He weren't alone.

04:27.702 --> 04:29.181
He were with a woman.

04:30.922 --> 04:32.968
How do you know that?

04:33.011 --> 04:35.318
I were there.

04:35.362 --> 04:38.713
Came to see Esme.

04:38.756 --> 04:41.193
They got to the door first.

04:41.237 --> 04:43.718
Well, what did
this woman look like?

04:43.761 --> 04:47.069
Older lady.

04:47.112 --> 04:48.766
Dark hair, I think.

04:48.810 --> 04:50.942
She were wrapped up.

04:50.986 --> 04:54.729
They let 'emselves in so quick
I couldn't get a proper look.

04:58.341 --> 04:59.908
I could've stopped 'em
if I'd known.

05:02.171 --> 05:03.912
They let themselves in?

05:03.955 --> 05:05.043
Wh-- Th-They had keys?

05:06.175 --> 05:08.177
Big ring of 'em.

05:09.178 --> 05:10.745
Where you going?

05:10.788 --> 05:13.356
The keys, they gave you
a clue, didn't they?

05:13.400 --> 05:15.010
Tell.

05:15.053 --> 05:17.055
No.

05:17.099 --> 05:18.100
I'm coming with
you, Sherlock.

05:18.143 --> 05:19.449
No. You're not.

05:19.493 --> 05:22.931
If you loved Esme
as much as I do...

05:22.974 --> 05:25.455
you won't deny me.

05:28.980 --> 05:31.896
You'll know how much
this means to me.

06:14.286 --> 06:16.332
For fuck's sake,
why'd you do that?

06:16.376 --> 06:18.943
Emotions got the better
of me. Sorry.

06:18.987 --> 06:20.902
Walk away.

06:22.860 --> 06:24.253
Now, let's have a look.

06:26.168 --> 06:28.039
Oh, it's not too bad.

06:28.083 --> 06:29.998
Now let's start
again, shall we?

06:30.041 --> 06:32.130
You gave over
the keys. Why?

06:32.174 --> 06:33.958
W-We do it all the time.

06:34.002 --> 06:36.178
There are other flats
in the building to be let.

06:36.221 --> 06:37.658
He looked like
a respectable buyer.

06:37.701 --> 06:39.007
It-it's normal procedure.

06:39.050 --> 06:41.575
When you heard
about Esme's murder,

06:41.618 --> 06:42.880
why didn't you say
anything to the police?

06:42.924 --> 06:45.405
I called the police immediately!

06:45.448 --> 06:48.538
T-Two detectives came,
and I gave them

06:48.582 --> 06:50.148
a full description
of the man

06:50.192 --> 06:53.064
and-and all the relevant
paperwork. Look, I swear.

06:55.284 --> 06:58.287
The police knew.

06:58.330 --> 06:59.810
Coppers.

06:59.854 --> 07:01.769
Bent as Judas,
the lot of 'em.

07:01.812 --> 07:03.553
Leave me alone now,
would you?

07:03.597 --> 07:06.382
Don't take your grump
out on me, duck.

07:06.426 --> 07:08.384
I'm not the enemy.

07:08.428 --> 07:09.864
What we gonna do now?

07:09.907 --> 07:12.170
We never see
each other again.

08:13.318 --> 08:15.146
PRIME MINISTER:
There's a telephone number
you can call for information

08:15.190 --> 08:17.279
about bloody trains
and parking.

08:17.322 --> 08:19.542
Is this too much?
Hmm?

08:19.586 --> 08:21.544
Oh, uh, no.
It's very fetching, ma'am.

08:21.588 --> 08:23.067
But this...
No.

08:23.111 --> 08:24.504
No. I think it's too much.

08:26.157 --> 08:29.813
Ma'am, this is
a serious problem.

08:29.857 --> 08:32.686
None of these secret
political societies

08:32.729 --> 08:34.862
have ever dared show
their faces in public before.

08:34.905 --> 08:39.301
This is a brazen show
of disrespect.

08:39.344 --> 08:40.694
THE QUEEN:
What a dreary poster.

08:40.737 --> 08:43.871
How on earth does Mrs. Gaunt
expect to draw a crowd?

08:43.914 --> 08:45.829
Mm, there'll be a crowd.

08:45.873 --> 08:48.440
A mob.
Screaming for blood.

08:48.484 --> 08:50.965
Or a general election,
at least,

08:51.008 --> 08:52.749
which would come
to the same thing.

08:52.793 --> 08:57.275
A hung parliament, martial law,
blood and anarchy, ma'am.

08:57.319 --> 09:01.584
You should write plays,
Prime Minister. So dramatic.

09:01.628 --> 09:04.282
No.

09:04.326 --> 09:05.588
No, it won't do.

09:05.632 --> 09:06.850
I do not exaggerate.

09:06.894 --> 09:08.591
Anarchy.

09:08.635 --> 09:10.375
The whole country
will be watching

09:10.419 --> 09:11.681
to see how we respond.

09:11.725 --> 09:13.378
We don't oppose order

09:13.422 --> 09:16.991
or strength
or new dawns, do we?

09:17.034 --> 09:19.646
I don't understand
what it is they want.

09:19.689 --> 09:21.865
Ooh, they're not Republicans,
are they?

09:21.909 --> 09:23.650
Oh, Lord, no.

09:23.693 --> 09:26.696
No, traditional
English fascists.

09:26.740 --> 09:29.873
Smart black uniforms,
thrash Johnny Foreigner,

09:29.917 --> 09:32.876
hang free thinkers
sort of thing. Childish stuff,

09:32.920 --> 09:34.922
but they're willing
to destroy half the country

09:34.965 --> 09:36.706
to get what they want.

09:36.750 --> 09:38.708
A national cleansing in blood
would be just the ticket.

09:38.752 --> 09:40.710
But under Royal authority.

09:40.754 --> 09:42.625
Yes, of course.

09:42.669 --> 09:46.629
But you'd have
to follow their orders

09:46.673 --> 09:50.067
or be forced into abdication.

09:52.592 --> 09:54.463
The Duke of Windermere
would be very happy

09:54.506 --> 09:56.770
to take your place.I believe I told you

09:56.813 --> 09:58.685
we shan't ever speak
of my wretched uncle.

09:58.728 --> 10:01.513
As you say, madam.
Nevertheless...Absurd.

10:01.557 --> 10:04.386
The people would never stand
for it.

10:04.429 --> 10:06.736
Mustard and coral,
have you gone stark mad, woman?

10:09.696 --> 10:12.394
I want your permission to use
the harshest available methods

10:12.437 --> 10:14.439
to crush this rally.

10:14.483 --> 10:17.660
Water cannon and rubber bullets,
deployed with brisk discretion.

10:17.704 --> 10:21.272
Perhaps one or two snipers
in reserve.

10:21.316 --> 10:23.100
Won't that make me look
awfully oppressive?

10:23.144 --> 10:24.972
Can't we just send in
those lovely horses?

10:25.015 --> 10:26.103
Isn't that the usual style?

10:27.714 --> 10:30.412
Well, we shall do that,
of course.

10:30.455 --> 10:32.980
But we must do more.

10:33.023 --> 10:34.677
In times of strife,
the people need

10:34.721 --> 10:37.158
to see and feel
the firm guidance

10:37.201 --> 10:39.464
of Your Majesty's
government.
No.

10:39.508 --> 10:41.684
I won't be goaded
into brutality.

10:41.728 --> 10:44.556
Horses and truncheons only.

10:44.600 --> 10:47.124
No rubber bullets.
No cannon, no snipers.

10:49.649 --> 10:50.737
Yes, ma'am.

10:55.002 --> 10:58.048
If I may...
That's all.

11:13.934 --> 11:15.675
UNDINE:
A public rally?

11:15.718 --> 11:18.025
We had a pact.

11:20.375 --> 11:22.943
I thought we understood
each other.

11:22.986 --> 11:24.727
Why is she doing this?

11:24.771 --> 11:26.294
Puzzling.

11:26.337 --> 11:28.383
What can she say
or do at a public rally

11:28.426 --> 11:32.648
that warrants the risk
of arrest? I don't know.

11:32.692 --> 11:35.651
A reckless mistake, perhaps.

11:35.695 --> 11:37.784
You should be guardedly happy,
my dear.

11:37.827 --> 11:41.570
Well, she exposes herself,
she exposes us.

11:41.613 --> 11:44.486
We have to respond with
our own counterprotest,

11:44.529 --> 11:46.270
or the No-Name League
will look weak.

11:46.314 --> 11:47.881
I will look weak.

11:47.924 --> 11:52.146
If Mrs. Gaunt wants to bare
her neck, don't stop her.

11:52.189 --> 11:54.496
Let the police
do your work for you.

11:54.539 --> 11:57.368
Do nothing, you mean?

11:57.412 --> 12:00.371
If you sit down by the riverbank
and wait long enough,

12:00.415 --> 12:04.245
the corpses
of your enemies float past.

12:04.288 --> 12:05.637
Chinese proverb.

12:05.681 --> 12:08.075
We're not in China.

12:08.118 --> 12:09.076
Of course.

12:09.119 --> 12:11.600
I'm just a loyal advisor.

12:11.643 --> 12:13.689
You're the leader.

12:13.733 --> 12:15.430
You must decide.

12:40.020 --> 12:42.544
Big rally tomorrow in the park.

12:42.587 --> 12:46.243
Stand up for your country
and take part.

12:46.287 --> 12:51.118
Say no to peace
and say yes to battle. Eh?

12:51.161 --> 12:52.554
Are we not men?

12:52.597 --> 12:53.947
Shut it, Adolf.
The game's on.

12:53.990 --> 12:55.949
Oi, you! Off the furniture!
Sharpish.

12:55.992 --> 12:58.778
We are talking about
the future of England.

12:58.821 --> 12:59.909
Fuck off!

12:59.953 --> 13:01.781
Commie drunkards.

13:01.824 --> 13:03.130
You call yourself English?

13:03.173 --> 13:05.349
Fucking liberty.

13:05.393 --> 13:06.742
PATRON:
You're ruinin' the
fucking football, eh?

13:06.786 --> 13:09.223
PATRON 2:
Fuck off.

13:09.266 --> 13:11.007
Do you want some?Lads. Lads!

13:11.051 --> 13:13.531
Go on, then.
Do something.

13:13.575 --> 13:15.664
DAVEBOY:
You know,
I don't get politics.

13:15.707 --> 13:19.363
You're born, you're fucked,
you die.

13:19.407 --> 13:20.974
That's the name
of this ship.

13:21.017 --> 13:23.585
Why worry which fucker's
on the bridge?

13:24.804 --> 13:26.370
Alfie boy.

13:26.414 --> 13:30.548
Night of the murder,
Curzon had a woman with him.

13:30.592 --> 13:33.595
Description sounds like
that charlady, Mrs. Pike.

13:33.638 --> 13:35.205
What description?
How do you know that?

13:35.249 --> 13:37.294
Long story.

13:37.338 --> 13:39.166
We need to track her down.

13:39.209 --> 13:41.168
No problem. Ready.

13:41.211 --> 13:42.952
Well, finish your
pint. Let's go.

13:42.996 --> 13:44.736
What, now?

13:44.780 --> 13:47.348
What, we're-we're tracking
her down now? This minute?

13:47.391 --> 13:49.132
You're gonna track her down.
I've got other business.

13:49.176 --> 13:50.873
What business?

13:50.917 --> 13:54.268
The police fucked
Esme's murder investigation.

13:54.311 --> 13:56.183
It was a cover-up.Why?

13:56.226 --> 13:58.663
Don't know.
I'm going to ask a policeman.

13:58.707 --> 14:00.230
You two, find Pike.

14:18.292 --> 14:19.510
Goddamn it.

14:20.642 --> 14:22.905
You're nervous.

14:22.949 --> 14:24.994
Of course I am.

14:25.038 --> 14:26.996
I haven't the faintest doubt
that you'll be marvelous,

14:27.040 --> 14:28.650
your speech will
be spellbinding,

14:28.693 --> 14:30.782
and the rally will
be a great success.

14:30.826 --> 14:32.001
Yes.

14:32.045 --> 14:34.264
Or the Tower.

14:34.308 --> 14:37.311
Success. Destiny.

14:37.354 --> 14:39.095
Well and good.

14:39.139 --> 14:41.141
A success.

14:41.184 --> 14:42.577
What then, Jimmy?

14:42.620 --> 14:44.274
Well, I think
I'll start

14:44.318 --> 14:46.711
by personally castrating
the prime minister

14:46.755 --> 14:48.539
and all his cronies.

14:48.583 --> 14:51.629
Then I'll put them out to starve
in the Aldgate gibbet.

14:52.979 --> 14:55.024
Jolly well deserved, I'm sure.

14:55.068 --> 14:58.810
But wouldn't mercy look
more statesmanlike, though,

14:58.854 --> 15:00.943
to the people
at large?
The people...

15:00.987 --> 15:02.423
love ferocity,

15:02.466 --> 15:04.555
and they love
a spectacle.

15:04.599 --> 15:06.601
I'll give them both.

15:06.644 --> 15:08.516
Christ.

15:08.559 --> 15:11.432
It's all
a bit daunting, isn't it?

15:11.475 --> 15:14.000
I mean, we're-we're
starting a civil war.

15:14.043 --> 15:16.132
Steel yourself, Frances.

15:16.176 --> 15:19.614
Make no mistake,
I come with a rod of correction.

15:19.657 --> 15:21.703
There must be bloodshed.

15:21.746 --> 15:23.313
There must be pain.

15:23.357 --> 15:26.403
That is how a new
and stronger nation is forged.

15:27.970 --> 15:29.406
Egg and omelets, old girl.

15:29.450 --> 15:30.712
You know that.

15:30.755 --> 15:33.584
Yes. Yes, you're right,
of course.

15:33.628 --> 15:37.414
Sorry. Just a...
touch of the old butterflies.

15:37.458 --> 15:39.503
We shall fight... and win.

15:41.853 --> 15:43.812
What if the queen...

15:43.855 --> 15:45.814
refuses to accept our victory?

15:45.857 --> 15:48.338
Well... we'll
reason with her.

15:48.382 --> 15:50.297
She'll do the right thing.

15:50.340 --> 15:52.255
Wh-What if she doesn't?

15:53.387 --> 15:55.171
Then she knows that her uncle

15:55.215 --> 15:57.913
is waiting in the Bahamas,
anxious to come home.

15:59.045 --> 16:00.394
The pretender?

16:00.437 --> 16:01.569
Never.

16:01.612 --> 16:03.353
Never?

16:03.397 --> 16:06.400
Do you think?A coward

16:06.443 --> 16:08.706
who fled the war,
practically a traitor?

16:10.273 --> 16:11.405
Trifle harsh.

16:11.448 --> 16:13.233
He's no Alexander, but...

16:13.276 --> 16:16.062
He's married
to an American divorcÃ©e,

16:16.105 --> 16:17.411
and he wears jewelry.

16:17.454 --> 16:18.760
How can we talk

16:18.803 --> 16:20.283
about restoring virtue

16:20.327 --> 16:22.633
and allow such a man
on the throne?

16:24.157 --> 16:26.333
Perhaps you're right.

16:28.552 --> 16:30.815
No. You areright.

16:30.859 --> 16:32.992
No doubt.

16:35.559 --> 16:38.214
In any case...

16:38.258 --> 16:41.522
the mere threat of the man is
useful to us, don't you see?

16:41.565 --> 16:44.003
The queen doesn't know
we won't countenance the man.

16:46.962 --> 16:49.182
Here am I, talking
about the queen's business.

16:49.225 --> 16:50.748
Absurd.

16:50.792 --> 16:54.056
I can hardly write
a decent sentence.

17:26.132 --> 17:28.134
Terrible habit.

17:28.177 --> 17:31.659
Smoking?Sneaking up on people.

17:31.702 --> 17:33.835
It's uncivilized.

17:33.878 --> 17:36.185
Hard to break old habits.

17:36.229 --> 17:38.231
And it strongly suggests
this conversation

17:38.274 --> 17:39.797
will not be amiable.

17:39.841 --> 17:41.843
That's your guilty
conscience talking.

17:41.886 --> 17:44.019
Conscience?
You flatter me.

17:44.063 --> 17:46.021
You know why I'm here.

17:46.065 --> 17:48.502
Not the faintest, old chap.

17:49.981 --> 17:53.072
You-- and by "you,"
I mean the police--

17:53.115 --> 17:56.423
you knew who killed Esme,
and you covered it up.

17:56.466 --> 17:58.120
A very serious accusation.

17:58.164 --> 17:59.817
Skip the bollocks. Talk.

18:00.949 --> 18:02.559
Supposing what you say is true.

18:02.603 --> 18:04.735
I wasn't on Esme's case--
why do you assume

18:04.779 --> 18:06.128
I know anything about it?

18:06.172 --> 18:08.609
You know everything.
It's your job.

18:08.652 --> 18:10.915
Flattery again.

18:10.959 --> 18:13.179
I'm not happy,
Mr. Aziz.

18:13.222 --> 18:14.789
I'm not happy at all.

18:14.832 --> 18:16.660
Was you to play ignorant,

18:16.704 --> 18:19.185
I can't be responsible
for my actions.

18:19.228 --> 18:20.751
Are you threatening me?

18:20.795 --> 18:22.449
Yeah. I am.

18:24.842 --> 18:26.931
Just wanted to be clear
on that point.

18:26.975 --> 18:29.020
I'd hate to capitulate
too early.

18:31.284 --> 18:33.503
Uh, bravo on cracking
the case, by the way,

18:33.547 --> 18:35.853
Someday you must tell me
how you did it.

18:37.290 --> 18:40.119
It's the usual sordid story.

18:40.162 --> 18:42.991
Esme's killer, Mr. Curzon,
is the bastard son

18:43.034 --> 18:44.819
of a very important man.

18:44.862 --> 18:46.386
A lord, in fact.

18:46.429 --> 18:50.041
Favors were called in;
the case was scuppered.

18:50.085 --> 18:52.392
What lord? Give me a name.

18:52.435 --> 18:53.871
Oh.

18:53.915 --> 18:56.004
That's more
than my life's worth.

18:56.047 --> 18:57.353
Literally.

18:58.615 --> 19:00.530
Cut my throat, if you must.

19:04.317 --> 19:06.493
Tell me where Curzon is now.

19:06.536 --> 19:08.190
I don't know.

19:08.234 --> 19:11.498
Like I said, Mr. Aziz,
I'm not happy.

19:11.541 --> 19:13.369
I'll make trouble.

19:13.413 --> 19:15.066
Bulls in china shops
ain't in it.I don't know

19:15.110 --> 19:16.894
where your man is.

19:16.938 --> 19:18.940
I expect
I could find out, though,

19:18.983 --> 19:20.942
if you gave me some time.

19:20.985 --> 19:22.248
I haven't got time.

19:22.291 --> 19:24.032
You could put
the Sweeney onto me

19:24.075 --> 19:25.686
as soon as I walk out there.

19:25.729 --> 19:27.122
Yes, I could do that.

19:27.166 --> 19:29.472
You'll have to trust me.

19:31.561 --> 19:33.824
You got 24 hours.

19:35.913 --> 19:38.481
Well, I'd better
get onto it, then.

19:38.525 --> 19:40.440
Now, how should I reach you?

19:46.315 --> 19:48.926
Fuck.

19:48.970 --> 19:50.928
If you ask me, they're
all bloody lunatics.

19:50.972 --> 19:53.235
Ravens, indeed.
They're crows, more like.

19:53.279 --> 19:55.368
Disgruntled crows.
You give them their head,

19:55.411 --> 19:57.848
they'll have us
back at war in a trice,

19:57.892 --> 19:59.633
never mind who with.Hear, hear.

19:59.676 --> 20:01.069
I hope you're gonna give 'em
a bloody good thrashing

20:01.112 --> 20:02.636
at this wretched rally.

20:02.679 --> 20:05.073
Don't you worry,
we'll show them what's what.

20:05.116 --> 20:08.424
Rather them than that
wretched No-Name League, eh?

20:08.468 --> 20:09.512
Hmm.

20:09.556 --> 20:10.905
At least the Ravens have

20:10.948 --> 20:12.211
proper respect for rank...

20:12.254 --> 20:13.212
and blood.

20:13.255 --> 20:15.170
A plague on both their houses.

20:15.214 --> 20:17.477
What's the matter with
just muddling along together

20:17.520 --> 20:19.261
as we always have done?

20:19.305 --> 20:21.089
PRIME MINISTER:
Hear, hear.Built an empire that way.

20:21.132 --> 20:23.309
Gentry, plebs,
muddling and...

20:23.352 --> 20:25.876
bodging along together.

20:25.920 --> 20:27.965
Arthur.Sir.

20:29.663 --> 20:32.927
Arthur's been with me here
nigh on...

20:32.970 --> 20:34.537
20 years.

20:34.581 --> 20:36.539
We couldn't live
without each other.

20:36.583 --> 20:38.019
Am I right, Arthur?

20:38.062 --> 20:39.716
No doubt,
Sir Francis.

20:39.760 --> 20:40.978
What is it?

20:41.022 --> 20:43.372
A telephone call
for the prime minister, sir.

20:43.416 --> 20:44.808
Oh.

20:44.852 --> 20:47.028
Excuse me, gentlemen.

20:52.163 --> 20:53.817
Yes?

20:56.516 --> 20:58.431
Yes, I'm...

20:58.474 --> 21:00.998
with him now, as it happens.

21:03.262 --> 21:04.698
No.

21:07.353 --> 21:09.268
No. Come here.

21:21.367 --> 21:24.283
Sit down, man.

21:24.326 --> 21:25.936
Sit down.

21:27.242 --> 21:28.722
Thank you, sir.

21:28.765 --> 21:31.594
I've told Lord Smytth
what's afoot,

21:31.638 --> 21:34.336
and I've assured him
you'll do your very best

21:34.380 --> 21:36.469
to resolve the
situation quietly.

21:36.512 --> 21:38.775
He quite rightly
wants to know

21:38.819 --> 21:42.039
why the situation
isn't resolved already.

21:42.083 --> 21:45.260
Yes, sir.
Uh, the vengeful young man

21:45.304 --> 21:49.003
pursuing your son is a highly
skilled SAS combat veteran.

21:49.046 --> 21:51.919
Hard to catch,
hard to kill.

21:53.224 --> 21:55.139
We can get him, sir, no doubt,

21:55.183 --> 21:56.402
but, um....

21:56.445 --> 21:58.447
it'll take some doing.

21:58.491 --> 22:00.449
At a high cost
in men and blood, perhaps.

22:00.493 --> 22:02.103
Oh, indeed, Prime Minister.

22:02.146 --> 22:03.496
A high cost.And then,

22:03.539 --> 22:06.325
I imagine, a good few
indiscreet mouths

22:06.368 --> 22:08.457
will need to be silenced,
I expect.

22:08.501 --> 22:10.024
Yes, sir.
That's usually the case.

22:10.067 --> 22:12.331
You needn't lay it on
so thick.

22:13.723 --> 22:16.160
I know I'll have
to pay for this.

22:16.204 --> 22:18.206
Get the thing done.

22:18.249 --> 22:20.077
Yes, my lord.

22:23.167 --> 22:25.213
I make no excuses for him.

22:25.256 --> 22:27.171
He's not right in the head.

22:27.215 --> 22:29.348
He never was.

22:29.391 --> 22:32.525
But no child of mine is going
to be hunted like an animal

22:32.568 --> 22:34.353
by a mere pleb.

22:36.180 --> 22:38.574
Whatever he
may have been accused of,

22:38.618 --> 22:42.012
he has noble blood in him.

22:42.056 --> 22:45.364
And blood... is blood.

22:45.407 --> 22:49.368
Oh, any father
would do the same.

22:50.456 --> 22:52.327
His mother...

22:52.371 --> 22:55.286
was the great love of my life.

22:56.592 --> 22:59.465
As for payment,
perish the thought.

22:59.508 --> 23:02.206
What are friends for?Humbug.

23:03.338 --> 23:05.427
What do you want?

23:05.471 --> 23:07.081
Goes without saying

23:07.124 --> 23:10.301
your splendidly loyal support
for me in the House

23:10.345 --> 23:12.521
has been most welcome.Essential, you mean.

23:12.565 --> 23:15.045
Mm, quite so.

23:15.089 --> 23:17.439
I should hate
to lose that support,

23:17.483 --> 23:19.093
for any reason,

23:19.136 --> 23:21.748
under anycircumstances.

23:25.882 --> 23:28.276
Protect my son,

23:28.319 --> 23:31.061
get rid of this SAS ruffian,

23:31.105 --> 23:33.412
and I promise you my vote.

23:35.675 --> 23:38.460
Under any circumstances.

23:40.984 --> 23:42.943
Your son is safe.

24:35.735 --> 24:37.258
WOMAN:
One, two, three. Testing.

25:04.851 --> 25:08.332
Martha, do you
know what time it is?

25:08.376 --> 25:10.552
I do.

25:10.596 --> 25:13.773
I figured you for
an early riser.

25:13.816 --> 25:15.601
What is this about?

25:17.733 --> 25:19.518
Just passing.

25:22.390 --> 25:24.087
Are you okay?

25:25.611 --> 25:26.960
Fine.

25:28.091 --> 25:30.311
Touch of the flu.

25:30.354 --> 25:33.836
You shouldn't stay
long. It's catching.

25:33.880 --> 25:36.012
I never catch stuff.

25:36.056 --> 25:38.188
What's the coffee situation?

25:39.320 --> 25:41.540
I'll call room service.

25:46.675 --> 25:49.809
So, the big Raven Society
rally today, huh?

25:49.852 --> 25:52.028
What are you guys
doing about it?

25:53.203 --> 25:54.553
Nothing.

25:54.596 --> 25:56.555
Undine Thwaite told everyone
to stay at home.

25:56.598 --> 25:58.948
No. Not those guys.

25:58.992 --> 26:00.254
You guys.

26:00.297 --> 26:02.256
CIA.

26:02.299 --> 26:04.563
Now, I'm guessing you're gonna
play a waiting game, but...

26:04.606 --> 26:06.129
I think that would be a mistake.

26:06.173 --> 26:07.957
The situation
could deteriorate fast.

26:08.001 --> 26:10.307
Look at me, Martha.

26:10.351 --> 26:12.614
I'm not CIA.

26:12.658 --> 26:14.485
I'm looking at you, Thomas,

26:14.529 --> 26:16.009
and I don't believe you.

26:16.052 --> 26:18.577
Well, I can't help with that.

26:20.666 --> 26:22.406
Anyhow, I'm here
to tell you

26:22.450 --> 26:24.713
that I'm okay with
the CIA thing.

26:24.757 --> 26:27.194
I didn't want you to think
it'd be a problem for me.

26:27.237 --> 26:28.587
So we can continue
working together.

26:28.630 --> 26:30.589
That's a whole other issue.

26:32.199 --> 26:34.723
Well, go on.

26:34.767 --> 26:36.595
Let's face it, Martha.

26:36.638 --> 26:38.248
I'm not CIA.

26:38.292 --> 26:40.642
But supposing I was...

26:40.686 --> 26:43.645
you're not really...
Agency material.

26:43.689 --> 26:45.168
The hell I'm not.

26:45.212 --> 26:46.909
Last week,

26:46.953 --> 26:48.694
whilst on
a three-day blackout drug spree,

26:48.737 --> 26:51.827
you mislaid my sister
at a satanist orgy.

26:51.871 --> 26:54.482
Just a tad bit unprofessional,
don't you think?

26:54.525 --> 26:56.789
You son of a bitch.
Unprofessional?

26:56.832 --> 26:58.573
Look at you.

26:58.617 --> 26:59.966
I have the flu.

27:00.009 --> 27:01.794
You're drowning in
scotch and pills,

27:01.837 --> 27:03.926
you haven't slept right in
ages, you've been crying,

27:03.970 --> 27:05.885
and you're the big-shot CIA man?

27:05.928 --> 27:07.974
Yeah, well,
if you're the benchmark,

27:08.017 --> 27:10.367
I think I can
measure up okay.

27:15.938 --> 27:18.462
I'm sorry.

27:19.942 --> 27:22.553
That was uncalled for.

27:22.597 --> 27:25.556
That's all right.

27:25.600 --> 27:28.864
Not in great shape
at the present.

27:28.908 --> 27:30.431
It's true.

27:30.474 --> 27:33.173
What happened to you
at Crowley's?

27:33.216 --> 27:35.218
Not up for discussion.

27:35.262 --> 27:37.133
You saw the Devil.

27:37.177 --> 27:39.266
No. No Devil.

27:39.309 --> 27:41.311
I did. I saw him.

27:41.355 --> 27:42.617
No, Martha, you imagined him.

27:42.661 --> 27:44.401
I wish.

27:46.839 --> 27:50.016
Crowley is a spooky guy.

27:51.931 --> 27:54.890
We both got spooked.

27:54.934 --> 27:56.500
Let's leave it at that,

27:56.544 --> 27:57.893
shall we?

27:57.937 --> 27:59.634
This coffee sucks.

27:59.678 --> 28:02.724
You want some scotch?

28:02.768 --> 28:04.683
Um...

28:05.814 --> 28:08.774
Yeah. Sure.

28:15.781 --> 28:16.912
Hello?

28:16.956 --> 28:18.914
AZIZ:
He's been gift-wrapped for you.

28:18.958 --> 28:20.742
Wapping Pumping Station.

28:20.786 --> 28:23.136
Come alone.

29:04.612 --> 29:06.788
You're up early.

29:06.832 --> 29:09.225
Work, Mum.

29:09.269 --> 29:11.271
You're up early, too.Yeah.

29:11.314 --> 29:14.317
Making breakfast
for your dad.

29:14.361 --> 29:15.754
He's up early, too.

29:15.797 --> 29:16.842
Yeah, work.

29:18.191 --> 29:20.584
Sir Francis has a function.

29:21.716 --> 29:23.544
My busy boys.

29:25.459 --> 29:27.243
Where are you going?

29:27.287 --> 29:28.897
West End.

29:28.941 --> 29:30.420
Meeting a client.

29:30.464 --> 29:32.683
Got time
for a bacon sandwich?

29:32.727 --> 29:34.337
Or boiled egg
and soldiers?

29:34.381 --> 29:35.686
No, Mum.

29:35.730 --> 29:37.471
Well, at least let me
give you a hug, then.

29:59.885 --> 30:00.842
Got to go.

30:00.886 --> 30:01.843
Don't want to be late.

30:01.887 --> 30:04.063
Well, you be careful.

30:04.106 --> 30:05.673
I love you, son.

